[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating trust manager implementation**\n\nI'm implementing a trust manager, and it feels a bit verbose. The SslManagerBundle requires a javax.net.ssl.TrustManager and specifically an X509TrustManager with three methods. The idea of trusting all might suffice for building, but I need to remember to import some necessary classes. Adding a permissive manager could make checkstyle unhappy, which seems excessive. Simpler alternatives might work. I wonder if I can still ensure the public API performs a request even without HTTPS verification. It’s a bit complex!\n\n**Implementing local lambda for SSL context**\n\nI’m working on implementing a local lambda, and I'm setting up an `AtomicReference<SslBundle>` to hold the applied bundle. The `ClientHttpConnectorBuilder` captures the settings' SSL bundle, which is pretty neat! I realize this approach avoids using the system default. Still, I could create an `SslBundle.systemDefault`, but it won’t be used in the connector, leading me to ensure the settings had a bundle instead. I need to confirm that the package passes the named bundle without testing the actual connector. Also, I must ensure to handle timeouts correctly!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_09bfe98b47a25d70016a3efc1954cc8195bf66ab98516ba3f3\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqPvwi7HHXAQtez3NkpvFNrJ9ku_6QRad5MQpSL91jW7UcLb6enU6uUcnKcH7z5BR09lxWaPAQ2OuCJJuXdJCyKbeIrARUmZwjQWYQF-AXlJ1rfMxnCIxxcPpASP0fpS29ssou3EMf8xxxV3Ey2AuNAkfuwFhJQX-K0OxTso_UVMlD1-A6NMoq4JjS-yS5NKZDqc1X1NTeeGAi7IPX17XMfZNw9OEqIGdf-u0IZJ4NogHSwlh6skzel91X2I80VYayYZIaJBJf5C0RmGl18dW5S7CelmSdj83RY9KfyGHXCIJfQPGbWRJbxEx_0V3I1NFIUcKuzPvYrtsIGRWnrMp8BF4CDlZYb1FCOn77VLkQKBoov1Tf7YYcz-HuUkPaRqIzC7h-A0uA6KsCLCOmy5yhzLjiqFITxRlu_ac9zB7iP6FnuJctBC_KgGwWAdPo1KNOejKcY37j8DMc-Dh-ZStvgh1F10fzJ9aeBEYg5beGyxquyy7gj_FOLid5QRa2YPkqluSi3LCDPBIqAu9Y0pI7gmKBe-aofSWHfC